Okay! Imagine you have a little toy that you want to throw far away, like a small ball. A sling is like a special little pocket made of cloth that helps you throw things really far. You put the ball in the pocket, hold the ends, and then swing it around in a circle before letting go. When you let go, the ball flies away super fast! It’s like a fun way to launch your toy into the air!

Okay! Imagine you have a big piece of soft clay. If you take your finger and press down really hard, you make a big hole or a mark in the clay. That’s kind of like what "gouge" means! It’s when you make a deep cut or hole in something, like wood or clay, by pushing or scraping really hard. So, if you gouge something, you’re making a big dent or a hole in it!

Okay! Imagine you have a big puzzle, and all the pieces fit together perfectly without any gaps or bumps. When you put it together, it looks like one big picture, and you can't see where one piece ends and another begins. 

When we say something is "seamless," it means everything works together really well, just like that puzzle, so you don’t notice any breaks or problems. It’s smooth and nice!

Okay! A gaffer is like the boss of the lights when people are making a movie or a show. Imagine you are playing pretend and you want to make it look really cool with bright lights. The gaffer is the person who makes sure all the lights are set up just right so everything looks nice and bright for the cameras. They help make the magic happen!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy top. When you spin it really fast, it twirls around and around, right? That spinning is like "spin" in science!

Just like your top can spin in different directions, these tiny particles can have different kinds of "spin." 

So, "spin" is like a little dance that tiny things do, and it helps scientists understand how they behave!

Okay! So, thrush is like when tiny germs called yeast grow too much in your mouth or on your tongue. It can make your mouth feel a little sore and look white, like you have some funny stuff on your tongue. It’s not super serious, and doctors can help make it go away with some medicine. Just like when you have a cold, you can get better!

Okay! Imagine you have a big chocolate egg. When you crack it open, you see that the inside is empty, and it’s just a shell. That empty space inside is what we call "hollow." So, when something is hollow, it means it has a shell or outside, but nothing is inside!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy that you really like, but you want to play with it right now instead of putting it away for later. Being "shortsighted" is like only thinking about having fun right now and not thinking about what might happen later. So, if you play with your toy all the time and don’t take care of it, it might break, and then you can’t play with it anymore. It’s important to think about the future too!

Okay! Imagine you have a yummy piece of cake, but then someone puts dirt on it. That dirt makes the cake look and taste really bad. When something is "nasty," it means it’s really yucky or not nice, just like that dirty cake! It can be something that smells bad, looks gross, or feels icky. So, "nasty" is when something is not good at all!

When you want to drink something, you pour it into the cup, and then you can lift it up to your mouth and sip! Cups can be made of different materials like plastic, glass, or ceramic, and they come in many colors and shapes.

Okay! Imagine you have a box of crayons with lots of different colors. If you take a red crayon and a blue crayon, and you want to make a pretty picture, you can mix them together to make purple. 

Now, if you want to make the purple color change slowly, you can add a little bit of red, then a little more blue, and keep mixing until you have a nice smooth change from red to blue. 

That smooth change from one color to another is like "gradation." It’s when things go from one thing to another in a nice, smooth way, like colors or sizes!

Okay! Imagine you have a big box of toys, and you want to keep them safe. A wall is like a big, strong fence that helps keep things inside a space, like your room or a house. It stops things from getting in or out, just like how a fence keeps your toys from rolling away. Walls can be made of different things, like wood or bricks, and they help keep us safe and cozy inside!

Okay! Imagine you have a long piece of string, and you want to keep it nice and tidy. A "reel" is like a special round holder that helps you wrap the string around it so it doesn't get all tangled up. You can think of it like a big round toy that keeps your string safe and easy to use whenever you want to play with it!

Okay! Imagine you and your friend are playing with toys, and you both want to play with the same toy at the same time. If you quickly grab the toy before your friend can, that’s like preemption! It means you took action first to stop your friend from getting it. So, preemption is when someone does something first to prevent someone else from doing it.

Okay! Imagine you have a big cup of juice, and you accidentally poke a tiny hole in the bottom. What happens? The juice starts to drip out, right? That’s called a "leak." 

So, when something leaks, it means something is coming out where it shouldn’t, like juice from your cup or water from a pipe. It’s like a little surprise that makes a mess!

Okay! Imagine you’re playing a game, and it’s really important to do well at the very end. When you do something super amazing and help your team win, even when it’s really hard, that’s called being "clutch." It’s like when you score the last point in a basketball game or make a great catch in baseball when everyone is watching. It means you did something really special when it mattered the most!

Okay! So, when someone is pregnant, it means that a baby is growing inside their tummy. It’s like when you plant a seed in the ground, and it starts to grow into a little plant. The baby takes time to grow, and when it’s ready, it comes out to meet everyone! It’s a special time for the person who is going to be a mommy.

Okay! Imagine you have a big, soft blanket, and you want to make it look nice and fluffy. When you shake it really fast, the blanket moves and fluffs up. That shaking is kind of like "lash."

So, "lash" can be about shaking something to make it nice or about saying something strong when you’re upset!

Okay! Imagine you and your friend are playing and you both want the same toy. You start to pull it back and forth a little bit, and maybe you bump into each other while trying to get it. That little bit of pushing and pulling is called a "scuffle." It's like a tiny fight, but usually, it’s just for fun and doesn’t hurt anyone!

Okay! Imagine you have a big box of crayons, and you want to guess what color your friend will pick next. You might say, "I think they will pick the blue crayon!" That's called speculating. Okay! Imagine you want to go to your friend's house. There are different paths you can take, like walking down the street or through the park. Each path is a "way" to get there. So, "way" means a path or a method to do something! It’s like saying, “This is the way to get to your friend’s house!”

Okay! So, when we say "lick," it means to use your tongue to touch something. Like when you eat an ice cream cone and you use your tongue to get the yummy ice cream off the cone. It’s like giving it a little taste!

Okay! So, wood is a special kind of material that comes from trees. Wood is hard and can be smooth or rough, and it smells nice, like nature! It’s like the tree’s way of helping us build and create things.

Okay! Imagine you have a really cool toy that all your friends want to play with. Because you have that toy, everyone thinks you’re super cool and wants to be your friend. That special feeling of being popular and having influence is called "clout." So, clout is like having a lot of friends who think you’re awesome!

A flute is a special kind of musical instrument that you blow into to make pretty sounds. It’s long and usually made of shiny metal or sometimes wood. When you blow air into one end and cover the little holes with your fingers, it makes different notes, kind of like magic! People play flutes in bands or orchestras, and the music can sound happy, sad, or even like a fairy tale!

Okay! Imagine you have a piece of fruit, like an apple. If you leave it out in the sun for a long time, all the water inside it goes away, and it becomes really dry and hard. That’s what we call "desiccated." It means something has lost all its moisture and is very dry, just like that dried-up apple!

Okay! A hawk is a big bird that can fly really high in the sky. It has sharp eyes to see things far away, and it can swoop down quickly to catch its food, like little animals. Okay! Imagine you have a superhero who always helps others, shares their toys, and is really kind. When someone is called "noble," it means they are like that superhero! They do good things, are brave, and care about other people. So, being noble is about being really nice and doing the right thing, just like a hero!

Okay! Imagine you are outside on a day when the air feels a little wet and you can’t see very far because everything looks blurry and soft. That’s what we call "foggy." Okay! Imagine you have a big box of playdough. When you take some playdough and shape it into a ball, that’s one form. If you squish it flat to make a pancake, that’s another form. So, "form" is just how something looks or what shape it is! It can be round, flat, tall, or any other shape you can think of!

Okay! A "whip" is a long, flexible tool that people use to make a loud noise or to help guide animals, like horses. Imagine a long piece of string that you can snap to make a "crack!" sound. Okay! Imagine you have a balloon. When you blow it up too much, it gets really big and then—POP! It goes boom and pieces fly everywhere! That’s what we mean by "explode." It’s when something bursts open really fast and makes a big mess!

Okay! Imagine you have a belt that helps keep your pants up. A buckle is the little part on the belt that helps it stay closed. It’s kind of like a magic door that opens and closes to keep your pants nice and snug!

Okay! So, a periwinkle is a little flower that is usually purple or blue. It grows in gardens and sometimes in the wild. It has pretty, star-shaped petals and is very nice to look at. There’s also a little sea creature called a periwinkle that has a spiral shell and lives in the ocean. So, periwinkle can be a flower or a tiny sea animal! Isn’t that cool?

A dog is a furry animal that is often a pet. They have four legs, a wagging tail, and they like to bark. Dogs are friendly and love to play, run, and cuddle with people. They can be big or small, and they come in many colors. Some dogs help people by being service animals, while others just like to be our best friends!

Okay! A toy is something you can play with. It can be a stuffed animal, a car, a doll, or even building blocks. Toys are fun because they help you use your imagination and have a good time. You can play with them by yourself or with friends!

Okay! Imagine you have a big box of crayons. Each time you get a new box, it has different colors and maybe some new crayons that weren't in the last box. 

A "generation" is like a new box of crayons. It’s a group of people who are born around the same time, like your friends at school. Just like how your crayons can be different from your older sibling's crayons, each generation has its own special things, like music, games, and ways of thinking. 

So, when we talk about generations, we’re talking about groups of people who grow up together and share things that are special to them!

Okay! Imagine you have a big box where you keep all your toys. Each toy is like a different file. When you want to play with a toy, you take it out of the box. When you're done, you put it back in the box. 

A file on a computer is like a toy in that box. It can be a picture, a game, or a story. Just like you can take a toy out to play with it, you can open a file to see or use it. And when you're done, you can save it back on the computer, just like putting your toy back in the box!

Okay! Imagine when you talk, your voice can go up and down, like a roller coaster! That’s called intonation. 

When you ask a question, your voice goes up at the end, like “Are you coming?” But when you say something happy, your voice might go up and down, like “I got a new toy!” 

So, intonation is just how we change our voice to show feelings or to ask things. It makes talking more fun!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy box, and you really want to play with a toy that’s stuck at the bottom. A "hack" is like finding a clever way to get that toy out without making a big mess. It’s a smart trick or idea that helps you solve a problem or do something better! So, when people talk about "hacking," they mean using their brains to figure out a cool way to do things!

Okay! Imagine you have a glass of cold water and you put it outside on a really chilly day. When you come back, you see little ice crystals on the outside of the glass. That’s what we call "frosty"! It’s when things get really cold and tiny bits of ice form, making everything look white and sparkly, like a winter wonderland! So, when it’s frosty outside, it means it’s super cold and you might see ice on the grass and trees!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy drum. When you hit the drum, it makes a sound. If you hit it really fast, it makes a lot of sounds in a short time. If you hit it slowly, it makes fewer sounds. 

"Frequency" is just a fancy word for how many times something happens in a certain time. So, if you hit the drum 10 times in one minute, we can say the frequency is 10 hits per minute! It’s like counting how many times something happens!

Okay! Imagine you have a big, stretchy rubber band. When you pull on it, it gets longer and thinner, right? That pulling is like "strain." Strain happens when something is stretched or pushed really hard. Just like the rubber band can get stretched, other things can feel strain too when we push or pull on them!

Okay! Imagine you have a really bright flashlight. When you turn it on, it makes a quick, bright light that you can see for a moment. That quick burst of light is what we call a "flash." It’s like when a camera takes a picture and it goes "flash!" to help make the picture bright. So, a flash is just a quick, bright light that happens really fast!

Okay! Imagine you have a big box of crayons, and each crayon is a friend. When you want to share your crayons or play together, you all connect and talk to each other. 

A "network" is like that! It's a way for friends (or computers, phones, and other things) to connect and share information, just like you share crayons and play together. So, when you want to send a message or play a game with your friends, you use the network to do that!

Okay! Imagine you have a really nice toy that you love. When you play with it and think about how fun it is, you feel happy and thankful for it. That feeling of being happy and thankful is what we call "appreciate." So, when you appreciate something, it means you notice how special it is and you feel good about it!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy that you really love, like a big robot. Sometimes, the robot might get a little dirty or its batteries might run out. Maintenance is like taking care of your robot to make sure it works well and stays fun to play with. 

So, you might clean it, put in new batteries, or fix any parts that are broken. That way, your robot can keep playing with you and be super cool!

Okay! Imagine you are playing a game where you have to walk in a straight line. When you take a step ahead, you are going "forward." It's like when you want to go to the playground, you walk forward to get there! So, "forward" means moving ahead or going in the direction you want to go.

Okay! Imagine you have a big box of toys, and sometimes you want to tell someone about what happened with those toys. A deposition is like when you sit down with a grown-up and they ask you questions about your toys, and you tell them everything you remember. It’s like sharing a story about your toys so everyone knows what happened!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy that is really, really good at being a toy. It works perfectly, and everyone loves to play with it. When we say something is "exemplary," it means it is a great example of how something should be. So, if you do something really well, like sharing your toys or being kind, we can say you are being exemplary! It means you are doing a super job that others can look up to!

Okay! Imagine you have a friend, and you want to play together. If you go to the playground and your friend comes with you, you are both going to the playground together. That’s what "accompany" means! It’s when someone goes with you or joins you to do something fun. So, if you go to the store with your mom, she is accompanying you!

Okay! Imagine you have a big box of crayons, and you want to pick your favorite color. To "determine" your favorite color means you think really hard about all the colors in the box and then decide which one you like the most. So, when you "determine" something, you are figuring it out or making a choice!

Okay! So, recess is a special time during the school day when you get to take a break from learning in the classroom. It’s like a fun playtime! You can go outside, run around, play games, and have fun with your friends. It helps you relax and get some energy before going back to learning. It’s one of the best parts of the school day!

Okay! Imagine you have a big, comfy chair or a soft spot on the floor. When you "sit," you put your bottom down on that chair or spot and rest your legs. It’s like taking a little break and being still for a while. You can sit to read a book, play with toys, or just relax. It’s a way to take a pause and feel cozy!

Okay! So, "profane" is a big word that means using bad or mean words, especially when we talk about things that are special or important. It's like when someone says something that makes people feel upset or disrespected. Imagine if someone said something mean about your favorite toy; that would be like using a profane word. It's better to use nice words that make everyone feel happy!

Okay! Imagine you have a special toy that you really love. When you play with it, you want to keep it just for yourself or maybe share it only with your best friend. That means it’s private! It’s something that you don’t want everyone to see or touch. So, when something is private, it’s like having a secret that only you or a few special people know about.

Okay! A "barrow" is like a big, round hill made of dirt. Sometimes, people long ago would put special things inside it, like treasures or bones, to remember someone who was important. It’s kind of like a secret place where we can learn about the past!

Okay! Imagine you have a favorite toy that you always play with at home. That toy is like a "native" thing because it belongs to your home and is made just for you. 

Now, think about a bird that lives in your backyard. That bird is also "native" because it has always lived there and knows how to find food and make a nest in that place. 

So, when we say something is "native," it means it comes from a special place and is really good at living there, just like your toy is special to you and your home!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy that can change its shape. When you press a button, it can become a car, and when you press it again, it can turn into a robot! 

Being "responsive" is like that toy. It means something can change or move to fit what you need. So, if you’re using a tablet or a phone, and you touch the screen, it changes what you see right away. It’s like the toy that listens and changes when you want it to!

Okay! Imagine you have a favorite toy that you play with all the time. You know how it feels, how it looks, and all the fun things you can do with it. That toy is familiar to you because you see it and play with it a lot. 

When something is familiar, it means you know it well and it feels comfortable, just like your toy!

Okay! A dream is like a little movie that plays in your head when you are sleeping. Sometimes, you might see fun things like flying, playing with your friends, or going on adventures. Other times, it might be a little scary or strange. But don’t worry! When you wake up, it’s just a story your brain made up while you were resting. It’s like your imagination is having a party while you sleep!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy box, and your mom says, "You can only put your toys in the toy box, not anywhere else." If you follow that rule exactly, you are being "strict." So, "strictly" means doing something exactly the way it is supposed to be done, without changing it or bending the rules. Just like putting your toys only in the toy box!

Okay! Imagine you have a big box of toys, and some toys are broken or not being played with anymore. Scavenging is like looking through that box to find the toys that you can fix or use in a new way. It’s like being a treasure hunter, finding things that others don’t want anymore and making them special again!

Okay! Imagine you have a really cool toy that you love a lot. Sometimes, you want to show your friends how much you like it, so you tell them how awesome it is or you let them play with it. That’s kind of like giving a tribute! 

A tribute is when you show respect or say nice things about someone or something special. It’s like giving a big hug with your words to show you care!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy car. When you push it, it goes forward, right? That’s movement! Movement is when something changes its place or position. 

Just like when you walk, run, or jump, you are moving your body from one spot to another. So, movement is all about things going from here to there!

Okay! Imagine you have a big, fluffy blanket that you like to sleep under. When you wake up in the morning, you get out from under that blanket and start your day. "Wake" means to stop sleeping and open your eyes to see the world around you! It's like when you turn on a light in a dark room, and everything becomes bright and fun again!

Okay! Imagine you have a big box of crayons, and you can choose any color you want to use to draw. Liberty is like having the freedom to pick your favorite crayon and draw whatever you like, without anyone telling you what to do. It means you can make your own choices and be yourself!

Okay! Imagine you are playing a game with your friends, and it's your turn to do something, but you don't want to do anything right now. So, you say "pass!" This means you are letting your turn go to the next person, and they can play instead. It's like saying, "I don't want to play right now, so you go ahead!"

Okay! Imagine you have a box of crayons, and you have them lined up in a row. If you want to change the way they are arranged, you can take the crayons from the row and put them in a column, like stacking them up instead of lining them up. 

So, if you have a row of crayons like this:

🖍️🖍️🖍️

And you turn it into a column, it looks like this:

🖍️  
🖍️  
🖍️  

That’s what we call "transpose"! It’s just changing the way things are lined up.

Okay! Imagine you have a big spider web. It's made of lots of strings that connect to each other. The web helps the spider catch food and stay safe. 

Now, think of the internet like a giant spider web, but instead of strings, it has lots of computers and websites connected together. When you want to find something, like a funny video or a picture of a puppy, your computer can "travel" along the web to find it, just like a spider moving on its web! So, the web helps us share and find things on the internet!

Okay! Imagine you have a big box of crayons. When you "retain" your favorite crayon, it means you keep it safe and don’t let anyone take it away. So, you hold onto it and make sure it stays with you so you can use it whenever you want!

Okay! Imagine you really want a big, yummy ice cream cone. That feeling in your tummy that makes you think about the ice cream and wish you could have it right now? That’s called desire! It’s when you really want something, like a toy, a snack, or even a fun game. It’s like your heart is saying, “I want that!”

Okay! Imagine you have a big box of crayons, and you want to make a new color. To do that, you take some red and some blue crayons and mix them together. When you do that, you get purple! 

So, "derive" is like mixing things together to get something new. In math or science, when we "derive" something, we take some information and use it to find out something else, just like making a new color from crayons!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy that is bent, like a funny-shaped straw. When you "unbend" it, you make it straight again, just like it was before. So, "unbend" means to fix something that is bent and make it straight again!

Okay! Imagine you have a big piece of paper, and you want to write a story. When you start a new part of your story, you can make a little space at the beginning of the line. This little space is called an "indent." It’s like giving your words a cozy spot to start, so everyone knows that something new is happening. It helps your story look nice and makes it easier for people to read!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy that you really like, and you want to give it a big hug. But if you hug it too tight, it can't breathe and feels squished. "Strangulate" is a big word that means to squeeze something so tight that it can't breathe or move properly, just like if you hugged your toy too hard. But we should always be gentle and let things breathe!

Okay! Imagine you have a big box of colorful blocks. When you take those blocks and put them together to make a tower or a house, that’s called building! You’re using your imagination and your hands to create something new. Just like when you draw a picture or make a sandcastle, building is all about making things with what you have!

Okay! Imagine the universe is like a really, really big balloon. Inside this balloon, there are lots of stars, planets, and even our Earth! Everything you see in the sky at night, like the moon and the twinkling stars, is part of this big balloon. The universe is so big that we can't even see all of it! It's like a giant playground where everything is super far away from each other, but it's all connected in one big space.

Okay! Imagine you have a toy that you don’t want to play with anymore. If you put it away and say, “I don’t want to play with this right now,” that’s like dismissing the toy. It means you’re not paying attention to it or you’re not interested in it anymore. So, to dismiss something is like saying, “I’m done with this for now!”

Okay! Imagine you have a toy, and your friend has a snack. If you say, "I will give you my toy if you give me your snack," that’s a deal! It’s like making a promise to trade something you have for something your friend has. Both of you get something you want!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy that makes a funny sound, like a bee buzzing. When you hear that sound, it makes you feel excited and happy, right? "Buzz" is like that feeling! It’s when something is really exciting or when lots of people are talking about something fun, like a new toy or a cool game. So, when we say there’s a "buzz," it means everyone is super excited and chatting about something special!

Okay! A pill is like a tiny, round candy that helps you feel better when you're sick. But instead of tasting sweet, it usually tastes a little funny. You take it with some water, and it goes into your tummy to help fix what’s wrong, just like magic!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy that you really like, and one day you play with it a lot more than usual. That means you are using it a lot, and it makes you super happy! 

Now, think of a spike like a big jump or a big increase in something. So, if we were to draw a line that shows how much you play with your toy every day, a spike would be a tall point on that line when you played a lot more than other days. It’s like when you suddenly get really excited and jump up high!

Okay! Imagine your brain is like a big, colorful playground. When you think, it's like playing on the swings or going down the slide. You have lots of fun ideas and pictures in your head, just like you have fun playing with your toys. So, when you think, you are using your brain to play with ideas, solve puzzles, or remember things, just like you play with your toys in the playground!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy that you really like, and you want to show it to your friend. When you turn the toy so your friend can see it, you are "facing" it towards them. So, "facing" means turning something so that it looks at someone or something else. Just like when you face your friend when you talk to them!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy car that you really want to play with, but your big brother is sitting on it. He is stopping you from playing with it. When we say "inhibit," it means to stop or hold back something from happening, just like your brother is stopping you from playing with your toy car. So, to inhibit is like putting a pause on something!

Okay! Imagine you are looking at a big picture of nature. A landscape is like that picture! It shows things like mountains, trees, rivers, and fields. It’s all the pretty stuff you see when you look outside. So, when you think of a landscape, think of a big, beautiful scene with lots of different things in it!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy that is broken, like a teddy bear with a ripped arm. "Fixing" is when you help make that teddy bear all better again! You might sew the arm back on or use some tape to hold it together. So, fixing is just making something that is broken work again or look nice again!

Okay! So, "cheer" is when you feel really happy and excited about something, like when your favorite team scores a goal or when you see a friend. When you cheer, you might clap your hands, jump up and down, or shout something nice like "Yay!" It’s a way to show that you are really happy and you want to celebrate!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy that you really like, but sometimes it can be dangerous or makes a big mess. If your mom or dad says you can't play with that toy anymore because it's not safe, that's like a "ban." It means you have to stop using it for a good reason. So, a ban is when someone says you can't do something because it's not good for you or others.

Okay! Imagine you have a big box of crayons. Each crayon is a different color, and when you put some crayons together, they can make a pretty picture. A "region" is like a special area or part of something. 

For example, if you have a big map of a country, a region could be a smaller part of that map, like where the mountains are or where the rivers flow. It’s just a way to talk about a specific place that has something in common, like the same kind of trees or animals. So, a region is like a little piece of a bigger picture!

Okay! Imagine you are playing with a ball. When someone throws the ball to you, you reach out your hands and grab it. That’s called "catching"! It’s like when you try to grab something that’s coming towards you. So, if you throw a ball to your friend and they grab it, they are catching the ball! It’s a fun game we play!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy car. When you push it on a smooth floor, it goes really fast, right? But if you try to push it on a carpet, it doesn't go as fast. That’s because of something called "friction." 

Friction is like a little force that tries to stop things from sliding. On the smooth floor, there’s less friction, so the car can zoom around easily. On the carpet, there’s more friction, so it slows down. 

So, friction is like a friendly helper that makes sure things don’t slide away too fast!

Okay! Imagine you have a big box of toys, and you want to play with your favorite teddy bear. When you "find" your teddy bear, it means you look through the box and see where it is. Once you see it, you can take it out and play with it! So, "find" means to look for something and then see it or get it.

Okay! So, "folk" is a word that means people, especially in a group or community. Imagine you have a big family or a group of friends. When you all get together, you can call that group "folk." It can also mean stories, songs, or traditions that people share with each other, like how your grandma tells you stories about when she was a little girl. So, "folk" is all about people and the fun things they share!

Okay! Milk is a yummy drink that comes from cows, goats, or even some other animals. It's white and can be cold or warm. People like to drink milk because it helps them grow strong and healthy. You can also use milk to make things like cheese, ice cream, and yogurt! Some people even put it in their cereal. It's like a special drink that helps us in many ways!

Okay! Imagine you have three long pieces of string or hair. If you take the first string and cross it over the second one, then take the third string and cross it over the first one, and keep doing that, you make a pretty twisty pattern. That’s called a braid! It’s like making a special twisty rope with the strings or hair. When you finish, it looks really nice and stays together!

Okay! Imagine you have a big box of toys. Now, let’s say you share your toys with your friends, and they all want to play with them. If you have the most toys and your friends come to play at your house, you can say you have a toy empire! 

An empire is like a big group of places or people that are all connected because one person or group is in charge. Just like you are in charge of your toys, an empire is when one big place has control over other smaller places. So, it’s like being the boss of a lot of friends who all want to play together!

Okay! Imagine you are sitting on your mom or dad's lap. Their legs are like a little chair for you to sit on. When you sit on their lap, you can cuddle, read a book, or just be close to them. So, "lap" is the part of their legs where you can sit and feel safe and cozy!

Okay! Imagine you have a big ice cube. When you touch it, it feels really chilly, right? That feeling of chilly is what we call "coldness." It’s like when you go outside in winter and the air feels cool on your skin. Coldness is when things are not warm, like ice cream or snow. It makes you want to wear a jacket or snuggle up in a blanket!

Okay! Imagine you have a toy horse. A saddle is like a special seat that you put on the horse's back so that you can sit on it comfortably and not fall off. It helps you ride the horse better, just like how a chair helps you sit at the table!

Okay! Imagine you have a big piece of paper, and it's all white with nothing on it. That white space is like "blank." It means there’s nothing there yet, like when you haven't drawn or written anything on it. So, when we say something is "blank," it just means it’s empty and ready for you to fill it with your ideas!

Okay! So, "mince" is when you take something, like meat or vegetables, and you cut it into really, really tiny pieces. Imagine if you had a big piece of apple and you wanted to make it super small so you could mix it into a cake. You would chop it up into little bits! That’s what it means to mince. It makes the food easier to cook and eat!

Okay! Imagine you have a special sticker that shows you are really nice and always do the right thing. When you share your toys, help your friends, and tell the truth, you keep that sticker shining bright. "Honor" is like that sticker! It means being good, kind, and doing what’s right, so everyone can trust and respect you. It makes you feel proud inside!

Okay! Imagine you have a big box of crayons, and you want to see which colors you like the best. A "test" is like when you take out a few crayons and try them on paper to see how they look. You might color a picture with each crayon to find your favorite one. So, a test helps you learn or find out something by trying it out!

Okay! Imagine you have a big box of toys, but there are some empty spaces in the box. Filler is like the soft, squishy stuff you put in those empty spaces to make the box look full and nice. It can be like pillows or soft balls that help fill up the gaps so everything looks neat and tidy! In stories or movies, filler is like extra parts that don’t really change the main story but help make it longer or fill in some space.

Okay! Imagine you have a plant that needs water and sunshine to grow big and strong. If you forget to water it and it doesn’t get enough sunlight, it starts to droop and look sad. That’s kind of like what "languish" means. It’s when someone or something isn’t feeling good or isn’t growing well because it’s missing what it needs, like love, fun, or care. So, when we say someone is languishing, it means they might feel a little sad or stuck, like that droopy plant.

Okay! Imagine you are playing hide and seek, and you want to find a really good hiding spot so that the seeker can't find you. When you finally find a place to hide and the seeker walks by without seeing you, you feel like you "escaped" from being found! 

So, "escape" means getting away from something or someone that you want to avoid, just like hiding really well in your game!

Okay! Imagine you have a balloon. When you blow it up, it gets bigger and bigger. If you keep blowing too much air into it, what happens? It goes "bang!" and pops! 

So, "bang" is a loud noise, like when something breaks or makes a big sound suddenly. It can be a balloon popping, a door slamming, or even fireworks going off! It's just a fun way to describe a big, surprising sound!

Okay! Imagine you’re playing outside, and it starts to rain. You might want to go inside to stay dry and safe. That’s kind of like a retreat! It’s when people decide to take a break from what they’re doing and go somewhere quiet or safe to think, relax, or feel better. Just like going inside when it rains!

Okay! Imagine you have a big box where you keep all your favorite toys, like action figures, dolls, or cars. A "collector" is someone who loves to gather and keep special things, just like you keep your toys. But instead of toys, they might collect things like stamps, coins, or even rocks! They enjoy finding new pieces to add to their collection and taking care of them, just like you take care of your toys.

Okay! Imagine you have a toy car that you like to play with. When you push it really fast and it bumps into a wall or another toy, it stops suddenly and makes a loud noise. That’s called a "crash!" It’s when something goes really fast and then hits something else, and it can make a big mess or noise. Just like when you fall down while running, that’s a little crash too!

Okay! Imagine you have some candies. If you have 2 candies and your friend gives you 3 more candies, you want to know how many candies you have now. 

To "calculate" means to figure out how many candies you have in total. So, you can count: 

1, 2 (your candies) 
3, 4, 5 (your friend's candies) 

When you count them all together, you find out you have 5 candies! That's what it means to calculate—it's like counting or adding things up to find out how many there are.

Okay! Imagine you have a toy box, and you want to open it to get your toys. When you press the button on the box, it makes a little sound, like "click!" That sound means the box is now open, and you can play with your toys. 

In the same way, when you use a computer or a tablet, you can use your finger or a mouse to press on pictures or buttons on the screen. When you do that, it makes a "click" sound, and it helps you open things or make things happen, just like opening your toy box!
